\"N-phosphoroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h3H,1H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"lactic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2,4H,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-(2-hydroxyacetoxy)propanamide equivalent alanine-glycolate depsipeptide unit\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine-glycolate depsipeptide unit\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface hydrogenation of CO2 gives formate/formic acid under reducing vent conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals is central to vent prebiotic chemistry and provides C1 feedstock needed for alanine precursor synthesis; this step connects vent geochemistry to later Cannizzaro/formamide chemistry. Supported by iron-sulfur world and hydrothermal carbon-fixation studies (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Hall, 1997).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal generation of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor/vent redox gradients, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2/CO hydrogenation on metal-rich surfaces yields reduced carbonyl compounds including methanal and ethanal.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduced aldehydes are required as direct Strecker substrates and as input to formose/cyanosulfidic routes; FT-type hydrothermal synthesis on magnetite/iron is widely invoked for producing aldehydes and alcohols from simple gases. Alanine literature identifies formaldehyde and acetaldehyde as key precursors while hydrothermal systems are plausible sources of such feedstocks (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cleaves et al., 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate and glyoxylate formation from CO2-derived carbon\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent, anoxic, reductive carbon fixation network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed reductive carbon fixation and C-C coupling generate alpha-ketoacids including pyruvate and glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a central alanine precursor in reductive amination and transamination pathways, while glyoxylate is reported as a key prebiotic intermediate in Fe2+-catalyzed protometabolic chemistry. This step is literature-guided but still partly network-connecting/speculative because direct alanine-specific vent pyruvate synthesis remains incompletely resolved. Supported by protometabolic alpha-ketoacid chemistry and Fe-driven carbon fixation concepts (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic production of HCN from reduced feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated subaerial geothermal field, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and sulfur-assisted redox processing of reduced C/N feedstocks yields cyanide inventory for Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is indispensable for Strecker, phosphoro-Strecker, and glycolonitrile-mediated routes to alanine. The alanine literature explicitly emphasizes HCN in Strecker and cyanosulfidic scenarios under UV/energy-driven surface environments. Mineral-assisted UV chemistry is grounded in cyanosulfidic prebiotic synthesis work (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic formation of glycolonitrile from formaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed surface waters, mild reducing conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Addition of cyanide to formaldehyde forms the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile, a canonical cyanosulfidic intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report specifically identifies glyconitrile/glycolonitrile as a key intermediate in cyanosulfidic pathways feeding amino acid synthesis. This node provides a literature-supported convergent precursor linking formaldehyde and cyanide inventories to alanine chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-ammonia route to dihydroxyacetone from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline evaporitic pool or hot spring, wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formose-type carbonyl homologation and rearrangement under borate stabilization gives triose intermediates including dihydroxyacetone in the presence of ammonia.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies formaldehyde-derived formose-ammonia chemistry and dihydroxyacetone as relevant to alanine formation. Borate stabilization of sugars and clays as concentrative surfaces make this a plausible surface route (Weber, 1987; Ricardo et al., 2004; Furukawa et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal or warm-surface conversion of dihydroxyacetone and ammonia to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-423K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm geothermal pool; literature notes rapid initial alanine-forming chemistry from dihydroxyacetone plus ammonia under hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia-assisted rearrangement and oxidation state adjustment of triose feedstock furnishes alpha-ketoacid character represented here by pyruvate as the networked central intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dihydroxyacetone is explicitly cited in the alanine literature as reacting with ammonia in hydrothermal settings to produce alanine rapidly in early stages. Representing pyruvate as the connected alpha-ketoacid intermediate is a necessary literature-aligned abstraction because pyruvate is independently established as a direct alanine precursor in reductive amination/transamination chemistry. This connection is partly schematic but justified to integrate two reported routes (Yamagata et al., 1991; Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cannizzaro-formamide route from formaldehyde and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"drying lagoon or irradiated surface pool; Cannizzaro disproportionation provides formic acid under alkaline conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde disproportionation supplies formic acid, which with ammonia yields formamide as a reactive C-N intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly highlights the Cannizzaro/formamide pathway as an alternative non-Strecker route to alanine, with formaldehyde leading to formic acid and then formamide. This reaction establishes the required formamide node used in a subsequent acetaldehyde-to-alanine-nitrile connection (Pizzarello & Holmes, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis of alanine nitrile from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral to mildly acidic aqueous surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia; cyanide addition gives the alpha-aminonitrile 2-aminopropanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical prebiotic route to alanine identified throughout the literature and is one of the best-supported paths. Surface mineral listing is included to satisfy the required schema, though direct alanine-specific mineral dependence is less established than the core Strecker chemistry itself. Supported by Strecker amino-acid synthesis literature and prebiotic reviews (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957; Cleaves, 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker synthesis of N-phosphoroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"near-neutral pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"DAP activates aminonitrile formation selectively from aldehydes, yielding an N-phosphorylated aminonitrile intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research findings explicitly identify phosphoro-Strecker synthesis with diamidophosphate at neutral pH as a selective route avoiding unnatural byproducts. This is a direct literature-guided alanine-precursor pathway (Gibard et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe2+-like hydrothermal protometabolic conversion of pyruvate and glyoxylate to alanine-related intermediates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-bearing mineral surfaces approximating Fe2+-rich conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic inert atmosphere; protometabolic aldol/retro-aldol redox network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iron-promoted aqueous ketoacid network interconverts pyruvate, glyoxylate, hydroxyacids, and related metabolites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The alanine literature highlights Fe2+-catalyzed chemistry at about 70 degrees C involving pyruvate and glyoxylate, producing amino-acid relevant intermediates through protometabolic transformations. The exact mineralized form here is an adaptation to the required hydrothermal agent schema, with the chemistry grounded in reported Fe-driven nonenzymatic metabolic-like networks; this step helps connect hydrothermal ketoacid chemistry to later alanine formation and ester-mediated assembly (Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis and reductive amination/transamination convergence to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prebiotic pools, geothermal cycling, possible phosphate-buffered interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multiple convergent processes deliver alanine: aminonitrile hydrolysis, dephosphorylation/hydrolysis of N-phosphoroaminonitrile, and nonenzymatic reductive amination/transamination from pyruvate; lactic-acid/related hydroxyacid chemistry can feed ester-amide exchange contexts containing alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This final convergence step intentionally collects the literature-supported terminal transformations to alanine: (i) hydrolysis of alanine nitrile from classical Strecker chemistry, (ii) hydrolysis of N-phosphoroaminonitrile from phosphoro-Strecker chemistry, and (iii) nonenzymatic alpha-ketoacid amination/transamination centered on pyruvate, which mirrors the biological alanine route and has prebiotic support. The literature also emphasizes that such syntheses are expected to produce racemic alanine, not inherently L-enriched alanine; the target name reflects user request while chirality remains unresolved (Strecker, 1850; Gibard et al., 2018; Bada, 1991; Muchowska et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2014; Weber, 1981).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic ester-mediated incorporation of alanine into depsipeptide chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycles in prebiotic pools, dehydration-driven ester-amide exchange\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alanine and glycolic acid condense through ester formation and ester-amide exchange to yield depsipeptide motifs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The alanine research set explicitly includes ester-mediated/depsipeptide pathways as relevant downstream prebiotic assembly chemistry because hydroxy acids lower activation barriers and help incorporate alanine into longer oligomers while avoiding diketopiperazine problems. This step ensures environmental flow from hydrothermal hydroxyacid production and surface alanine synthesis into biochemical assembly (Forsythe et al., 2015).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldehyde to classical Strecker alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-derived acetaldehyde feeds the canonical Strecker route through alanine nitrile and subsequent hydrolysis to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal aldehyde to phosphoro-Strecker alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde reacts with HCN and DAP at near-neutral surface conditions to form N-phosphoroalanine nitrile, then hydrolyzes to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cannizzaro-formamide-assisted alanine route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde is converted with formic acid and ammonia to formamide, reflecting the non-Strecker Cannizzaro/formamide concept before convergence onto alanine chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile branch to alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic chemistry forms glycolonitrile from formaldehyde and HCN, a literature-reported amino acid precursor branch that converges on alanine-producing nitrile chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-ammonia to dihydroxyacetone to pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde enters formose-ammonia chemistry to produce dihydroxyacetone, which is connected to pyruvate and then to alanine via ketoacid amination.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrothermal pyruvate to alanine by reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal mineral networks generate pyruvate, which converges directly to alanine through prebiotic ketoacid amination/transamination chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe-driven glyoxylate-pyruvate protometabolic branch to alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-rich protometabolism produces glyoxylate and pyruvate and related hydroxyacids, which feed alanine chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Energy-driven HCN inventory feeding Strecker alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"UV/photochemical generation of cyanide inventory from reduced surface feedstocks supports alanine nitrile formation and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde plus acetaldehyde dual-feed convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal aldehydes generated together feed parallel surface branches: formaldehyde supports HCN/glycolonitrile/formose chemistry while acetaldehyde enters Strecker chemistry, all converging on alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Alanine onward into depsipeptide assembly\",\n      \"description\": \"After alanine formation, hydrothermal hydroxyacid inventory enables ester-mediated b