l synthesis on magnetite/iron is widely invoked for producing aldehydes and alcohols from simple gases. Alanine literature identifies formaldehyde and acetaldehyde as key precursors while hydrothermal systems are plausible sources of such feedstocks (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Cleaves et al., 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate and glyoxylate formation from CO2-derived carbon", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent, anoxic, reductive carbon fixation network"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed reductive carbon fixation and C-C coupling generate alpha-ketoacids including pyruvate and glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is a central alanine precursor in reductive amination and transamination pathways, while glyoxylate is reported as a key prebiotic intermediate in Fe2+-catalyzed protometabolic chemistry. This step is literature-guided but still partly network-connecting/speculative because direct alanine-specific vent pyruvate synthesis remains incompletely resolved. Supported by protometabolic alpha-ketoacid chemistry and Fe-driven carbon fixation concepts (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface cyanosulfidic production of HCN from reduced feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated subaerial geothermal field, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and sulfur-assisted redox processing of reduced C/N feedstocks yields cyanide inventory for Strecker and cyanosulfidic chemistry.", "reasoning": "HCN is indispensable for Strecker, phosphoro-Strecker, and glycolonitrile-mediated routes to alanine. The alanine literature explicitly emphasizes HCN in Strecker and cyanosulfidic scenarios under UV/energy-driven surface environments. Mineral-assisted UV chemistry is grounded in cyanosulfidic prebiotic synthesis work (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Cyanosulfidic formation of glycolonitrile from formaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed surface waters, mild reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "Addition of cyanide to formaldehyde forms the cyanohydrin glycolonitrile, a canonical cyanosulfidic intermediate.", "reasoning": "The research report specifically identifies glyconitrile/glycolonitrile as a key intermediate in cyanosulfidic pathways feeding amino acid synthesis. This node provides a literature-supported convergent precursor linking formaldehyde and cyanide inventories to alanine chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Formose-ammonia route to dihydroxyacetone from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and montmorillonite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline evaporitic pool or hot spring, wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Formose-type carbonyl homologation and rearrangement under borate stabilization gives triose intermediates including dihydroxyacetone in the presence of ammonia