ere/UV/electrical discharge cyanide source or a more defensible geochemical source.\",\n        \"State how HCN is concentrated and transported to the Strecker environment.\",\n        \"Disaggregate nitrile hydrolysis from other alanine-forming modes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.5\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.63,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.74,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.81,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.71,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.7,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is one of the better connected pathways because it explicitly exploits dual hydrothermal feedstocks and converges on alanine-relevant intermediates. It benefits from plausible formaldehyde and Strecker chemistry and captures the network's intended cross-environment flow. The main weaknesses are still the overstated hydrothermal aldehyde generation, the unsupported HCN source, and the over-aggregated final hydrolysis/amination step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use a better documented route for cyanide production or import.\",\n        \"Distinguish the glycolonitrile branch from the acetaldehyde-Strecker branch more explicitly.\",\n        \"Provide individual final reactions for alanine nitrile hydrolysis and pyruvate amination.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.84\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.81,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.77,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.76,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.8,\n      \"feedback\": \"This downstream pathway is well aligned with literature on est