C3H9N3O3P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"diamidophosphoric acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"diamidophosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H8N3O3P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"[(1-cyanoethyl)amino]phosphoramidic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-phosphoroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH5N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH5N/c1-2/h2H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H5NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyiminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine oxime precursor\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde and formic acid inventory\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\",\n        \"mol_006\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like conditions; H2-rich; carbon-fixation inventory-generating step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 yields reduced C1 products, with formate/formic acid as the better-supported product and formaldehyde included as a connected reduced-carbon inventory intermediate feeding surface chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is strongly supported in hydrothermal origin-of-life studies and motivates reduced C1 feedstock generation in alkaline vents (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007). The alanine-focused literature highlights formaldehyde as a required precursor in hydrothermal and surface alanine networks, although direct vent formaldehyde accumulation remains less certain; therefore this connected inventory step is partly speculative but necessary to connect the documented formose, Cannizzaro, and HMT-related precursor chemistry (reviewed in the provided knowledge base; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of acetaldehyde from reduced carbon inventory\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_007\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and elemental iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor or vent-wall Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive hydrogenation and C-C coupling on metal/mineral surfaces generate low-molecular-weight aldehydes including acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary identifies acetaldehyde as the central Strecker carbonyl precursor for alanine and notes hydrothermal production of simple organics under reducing conditions, but direct alanine-specific evidence for acetaldehyde formation is indirect. This step is therefore a constrained connecting reaction based on Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal chemistry for simple aldehyde generation rather than an alanine-specific experimental observation (Shock & Schulte, 1990; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; McCollom & Seewald, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface energy-driven synthesis of hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\",\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalytic surfaces and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"UV/energy-driven atmospheric-surface interface; reducing local chemistry; inventory-generation step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and energy-driven conversion of simple reduced C/N feedstocks generates cyanide that accumulates in surface waters and evaporitic settings.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary explicitly supports UV and energy-driven synthesis of amino acid precursor inventories and identifies HCN as a central precursor for Strecker, cyanosulfidic, and phosphoro-Strecker chemistry. The exact atmospheric microchemistry is not resolved in the provided report, so this node represents the experimentally supported existence of HCN-generating energy-driven surface chemistry rather than a single uniquely established stoichiometric route (Miller, 1953; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983; Kobayashi et al., 1990; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic formation of glycinenitrile from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\",\n        \"mol_004\",\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_008\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\",\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals and UV-active TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic pool; mild surface conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia and cyanide through imine/aminonitrile chemistry to give glycinenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The knowledge base specifically notes the cyanosulfidic scenario beginning with glyconitrile/glycinenitrile from formaldehyde and HCN as a plausible prebiotic amino-acid precursor branch. This is a literature-grounded route for generating aminonitrile inventory that can feed alanine synthesis indirectly by C1 homologation chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; reviewed in the provided knowledge base).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Cannizzaro-type oxidation-reduction of formaldehyde to formic acid and methanol equivalent feeding formamide chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_006\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\",\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and TiO2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline evaporitic pool; concentrating wet-dry cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Disproportionation of formaldehyde under alkaline concentrating conditions supplies formic acid for the formamide/Cannizzaro branch.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The provided report explicitly identifies the Cannizzaro pathway as an alternative non-Strecker route in which formaldehyde yields formic acid that then reacts with ammonia to generate formamide-related chemistry leading to alanine. This reaction encodes the literature-supported entry into that branch; the omitted reduced coproduct is not tracked because it is not required for connectivity to alanine (Kebukawa et al., 2017 as reflected in the provided report; also consistent with prebiotic formaldehyde disproportionation chemistry).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface condensation of formic acid and ammonia to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_006\",\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_009\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and borate-rich drying surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"dry-down or geothermal heating; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrative amidation during surface concentration converts formic acid and ammonia to formamide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is explicitly named in the research summary as a key intermediate in the Cannizzaro-derived alanine pathway. Surface dehydration chemistry is widely invoked for formamide generation under prebiotic conditions, and here it is used conservatively to connect the reported formic-acid/formamide alanine route (Saladino et al., 2012; Kebukawa et al., 2017 as summarized in the provided research findings).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface formose reaction to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_010\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"bor