uding it as a downstream product of formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde chemistry follows the reported formose-ammonia framework (Weber, 2001; Taillades et al., 1999 as reflected in the provided report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe2+-network synthesis of pyruvate and glyoxylate from reduced carbon feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\",\n        \"mol_006\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_012\",\n        \"mol_013\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-rich sulfide mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"70C inert, anoxic aqueous network; protometabolic aldol/retro-aldol redox chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe2+-driven protometabolic network chemistry interconverts reduced carbonyl compounds to central ketoacids including pyruvate and glyoxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research findings explicitly cite Fe2+-catalyzed prebiotic networks at 70C under inert atmosphere that generate amino-acid-relevant intermediates including pyruvate and glyoxylate through aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration, decarboxylation, and redox chemistry. This is one of the best-supported non-Strecker entries into alanine precursor space (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal conversion of dihydroxyacetone and ammonia to pyruvate-linked alanine precursor pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_011\",\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_012\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"pyrite (FeS2)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n    