"diamidophosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H8N3O3P", "iupac_name": "[(1-cyanoethyl)amino]phosphoramidic acid", "common_name": "N-phosphoroalanine nitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CH5N", "iupac_name": "methanamine", "common_name": "methylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH5N/c1-2/h2H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C3H5NO3", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyiminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine oxime precursor", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde and formic acid inventory", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like conditions; H2-rich; carbon-fixation inventory-generating step"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated reduction of CO2 by H2 yields reduced C1 products, with formate/formic acid as the better-supported product and formaldehyde included as a connected reduced-carbon inventory intermediate feeding surface chemistry.", "reasoning": "CO2 reduction to formate on Fe-S minerals is strongly supported in hydrothermal origin-of-life studies and motivates reduced C1 feedstock generation in alkaline vents (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007). The alanine-focused literature highlights formaldehyde as a required precursor in hydrothermal and surface alanine networks, although direct vent formaldehyde accumulation remains less certain; therefore this connected inventory step is partly speculative but necessary to connect the documented formose, Cannizzaro, and HMT-related precursor chemistry (reviewed in the provided knowledge base; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of acetaldehyde from reduced carbon inventory", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and elemental iron", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor or vent-wall Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Successive hydrogenation and C-C coupling on metal/mineral surfaces generate low-molecular-weight aldehydes including acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The literature summary identifies acetaldehyde as the central Strecker carbonyl precursor for alanine and notes hydrothermal production of simple organics under reducing conditions, but direct alanine-specific evidence for acetaldehyde formation is indirect. This step is therefore a constrained connecting reaction based on Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal chemistry for simple aldehyde generation rather than an alanine-specific experimental observation (Shock & Schulte, 1990; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; McCollom & Seewald, 2007)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface energy-driven synthesis of hydrogen cyanide", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalytic surfaces and sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "UV/energy-driven atmospheric-surface interface; reducing local chemistry; inventory-generation step"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical and energy-driven conversion of simple reduced C/N feedstocks generates cyanide that accumulates in surface waters and evaporitic settings.", "reasoning": "The research summary explicitly supports UV and energy-driven synthesis of amino acid precursor inventories and identifies HCN as a central precursor for Strecker, cyanosulfidic, and phosphoro-Strecker chemistry. The exact atmospheric microchemistry is not resolved in the provided report, so this node represents the experimentally supported existence of HCN-generating energy-driven surface chemistry rather than a single uniquely established stoichiometric route (Miller, 1953; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983; Kobayashi et al., 1990; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Cyanosulfidic formation of glycinenitrile from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals and UV-active TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated cyanosulfidic pool; mild surface conditions"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia and cyanide through imine/aminonitrile chemistry to give glycinenitrile.", "reasoning": "The knowledge base specifically notes the cyanosulfidic scenario beginning with glyconitrile/glycinenitrile from formaldehyde and HCN as a plausible prebiotic amino-acid precursor branch. This is a literature-grounded route for generating aminonitrile inventory that can feed alanine synthesis indirectly by C1 homologation chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; reviewed in the provided knowledge base)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface Cannizzaro-type oxidation-reduction of formaldehyde to formic acid and methanol equivalent feeding formamide chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and TiO2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline evaporitic pool; concentrating wet-dry cycles"}, "mechanism": "Disproportionation of formaldehyde under alkaline concentrating conditions supplies formic acid for the formamide/Cannizzaro branch.", "reasoning": "The provided report explicitly identifies the Cannizzaro pathway as an alternative non-Strecker route in which formaldehyde yields formic acid that then reacts with ammonia to generate formamide-related chemistry leading to alanine. This reaction encodes the literature-supported entry into that branch; the omitted reduced coproduct is not tracked because it is not required for connectivity to alanine (Kebukawa et al., 2017 as reflected in the provided report; also consistent with prebiotic formaldehyde disproportionation chemistry)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface condensation of formic acid and ammonia to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and borate-rich drying surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "dry-down or geothermal heating; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrative amidation during surface concentration converts formic acid and ammonia to formamide.", "reasoning": "Formamide is explicitly named in the research summary as a key intermediate in the Cannizzaro-derived alanine pathway. Surface dehydration chemistry is widely invoked for formamide generation under prebiotic conditions, and here it is used conservatively to connect the reported formic-acid/formamide alanine route (Saladino et al., 2012; Kebukawa et al., 2017 as summarized in the provided research findings)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface formose reaction to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline evaporitic pool; borate stabilizes sugars"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes aldol-type oligomerization; borate stabilization allows accumulation of glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The literature synthesis explicitly identifies formaldehyde polymerization to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde as important precursor chemistry relevant to alanine formation through formose-ammonia networks. Borate-stabilized sugar chemistry is a standard prebiotic connection from C1 to C2-C3 carbonyls (Ricardo et al., 2004; Weber, 2001; reviewed in the provided knowledge base)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface conversion of glycolaldehyde to dihydroxyacetone in formose-ammonia chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline formose network; wet-dry concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Further aldol/isomerization chemistry in the formose network gives a C3 ketose pool including dihydroxyacetone.", "reasoning": "Dihydroxyacetone is specifically identified in the alanine literature summary as a hydrothermal/surface-relevant precursor that can react with ammonia to yield alanine-related products rapidly in early reaction phases. Including it as a downstream product of formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde chemistry follows the reported formose-ammonia framework (Weber, 2001; Taillades et al., 1999 as reflected in the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe2+-network synthesis of pyruvate and glyoxylate from reduced carbon feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe2+-rich sulfide mineral environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "70C inert, anoxic aqueous network; protometabolic aldol/retro-aldol redox chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Fe2+-driven protometabolic network chemistry interconverts reduced carbonyl compounds to central ketoacids including pyruvate and glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "The research findings explicitly cite Fe2+-catalyzed prebiotic networks at 70C under inert atmosphere that generate amino-acid-relevant intermediates including pyruvate and glyoxylate through aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration, decarboxylation, and redox chemistry. This is one of the best-supported non-Strecker entries into alanine precursor space (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrothermal conversion of dihydroxyacetone and ammonia to pyruvate-linked alanine precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "metal sulfide/oxide hydrothermal surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "approx. 150C hydrothermal simulation; ammonia-rich"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia-driven rearrangement/dehydration/oxidation of dihydroxyacetone generates pyruvate-equivalent carbonyl chemistry feeding alanine formation.", "reasoning": "The report specifically states that dihydroxyacetone reacts with ammonia in hydrothermal settings to produce alanine rapidly in the initial reaction phase. Because the detailed intermediate sequence is not fully specified in the summary, this node conservatively encodes a pyruvate-linked precursor conversion instead of an unjustified direct jump to alanine, correcting the overcompression problem noted in prior attempts (Taillades et al., 1999; Marshall-Bowman et al., 2010 as reflected in the provided knowledge base)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Classical surface Strecker synthesis of alanine nitrile from acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite concentrating surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral to mildly acidic aqueous surface setting; evaporitic concentration"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, cyanide adds to the iminium, and the resulting alpha-aminonitrile is alanine nitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical prebiotic alanine route identified repeatedly in the literature summary: acetaldehyde + HCN + NH3 gives an alpha-aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to alanine. The reaction is well established as Strecker chemistry under plausible prebiotic conditions (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953; Bada, 2013 review context; specifically cited in the provided knowledge base as source 15634)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface phosphoro-Strecker synthesis of N-phosphoroalanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate mineral environment with DAP", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH; selective aldehyde targeting"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde reacts with HCN and diamidophosphate to form a phosphorylated aminonitrile intermediate.", "reasoning": "The research report explicitly highlights phosphoro-Strecker synthesis as a literature-supported alanine route in which aldehydes react with DAP and HCN at neutral pH to form N-phosphoroaminonitriles that hydrolyze to amino acids while suppressing side products. This reaction follows that reported chemistry directly (Powner and co-workers; Gibard et al., 2018 as represented by source 21192 in the provided knowledge base)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis of alanine nitrile to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling or prolonged standing"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the alpha-aminonitrile to the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitriles to alpha-amino acids is the defining second stage of Strecker chemistry and is explicitly part of the reported alanine synthesis route. Prebiotically this is expected to generate racemic alanine, not intrinsic L-selective alanine; the target is labeled L-alanine only because requested, with chirality selection remaining unresolved in the literature (Miller, 1953; Peltzer et al., 1984; Bada, 2013 review context; knowledge-base summary of Strecker pathway)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrolysis of N-phosphoroalanine nitrile to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral aqueous hydrolysis following phosphorylation-enabled capture"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic dephosphorylation and nitrile hydrolysis release alanine from the phosphoroaminonitrile precursor.", "reasoning": "The provided literature report states that N-phosphoroaminonitriles formed in phosphoro-Strecker chemistry undergo hydrolysis to amino acids. This step directly encodes that documented transformation, again with the caveat that prebiotic product distributions are expected to be racemic without an additional chiral selection process (Gibard et al., 2018; source 21192 in the provided knowledge base)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Cannizzaro-formamide route from formamide and acetaldehyde to alanine nitrile-equivalent precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "drying mineral surface", "aqueous": "false", "other": "formamide-rich drying film; non-Strecker alternative represented as connected aminonitrile-producing branch"}, "mechanism": "Formamide-derived nucleophilic carbon-nitrogen chemistry reacts with acetaldehyde to generate alanine-forming aminated C3 precursor chemistry, represented here by convergence onto the alanine nitrile node.", "reasoning": "The knowledge base explicitly identifies a non-Strecker Cannizzaro/formamide pathway in which formaldehyde gives formic acid, then formamide, and a carbamyl/carbanion equivalent derived from formamide reacts with acetaldehyde to produce alanine. Because the report does not provide a uniquely standardized isolated intermediate node compatible with the required network schema, this reaction is encoded as convergence onto the alanine nitrile-equivalent precursor pool rather than an unsupported direct single-step alanine claim. This addresses prior feedback about omitting the key formamide branch while avoiding an overcompressed terminal reaction (Kebukawa et al., 2017; as summarized in source 5960 of the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-343K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic aqueous setting; hydrothermal feedstocks transferred into prebiotic pool"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia followed by reduction to alanine.", "reasoning": "The literature summary explicitly includes reductive amination of alpha-keto acids as a prebiotic alanine pathway and identifies pyruvate as a key precursor. Because the deep report does not specify a single universally accepted mineral catalyst for this exact alanine-forming step, it is represented in the Biochemical/prebiotic stage rather than as a hydrothermal mineral reaction. This avoids inventing unsupported catalyst detail while following the reported chemistry (Kitadai, 2016 review context; source 15293 in the provided knowledge base)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Non-enzymatic transamination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-303K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous phosphate-buffer-like conditions; mild temperature"}, "mechanism": "Amine transfer to the alpha-keto acid scaffold converts pyruvate into alanine in a biomimetic non-enzymatic process.", "reasoning": "The report specifically mentions non-enzymatic transamination in aqueous phosphate buffers at 25-30C as a relevant prebiotic analog of the modern biological route from pyruvate to alanine. This is a distinct pathway from reductive amination and therefore is retained separately (source 1024 in the provided knowledge base; modern biochemical analog summarized in source 6940)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Formose-ammonia conversion of glycolaldehyde to acetaldehyde precursor pool", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay and borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline formose-ammonia network; concentration by wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia-assisted carbonyl rearrangement and reduction within the formose network generates C2 aldehyde inventory feeding Strecker chemistry.", "reasoning": "The formose-ammonia literature summarized in the provided report links formaldehyde-derived carbonyl networks to alanine formation and emphasizes that additional formaldehyde is needed for alanine production relative to glycine. The exact detailed intermediate map is complex; this reaction provides the minimal literature-consistent connection from sugar-carbonyl chemistry to the acetaldehyde hub required by Strecker alanine synthesis, and is therefore a justified bridging step rather than a free invention (Weber, 2001; source 13498 in the provided knowledge base)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Hydrothermal Al-rich smectite promoted conversion of formaldehyde and ammonia to pyruvate-linked precursor inventory", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe-bearing hydrothermal minerals; literature notes Al-rich smectite enhancement but required network minerals are Fe-minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH about 10; 150C hydrothermal simulation; long residence time"}, "mechanism": "Hydrothermal carbonyl-ammonia chemistry generates higher-carbon keto-acid precursor pools that converge on pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The supplied literature emphasizes hydrothermal synthesis of alanine from formaldehyde/ammonia-rich systems at about 150C and pH 10, with Al-rich smectites enhancing alanine yield to about 60 uM after 31 days. Because the schema restricts hydrothermal mineral agents to a required Fe-mineral list, this node encodes the hydrothermal precursor-generating chemistry under the reported conditions while acknowledging in reasoning that the strongest alanine-specific catalyst evidence is for Al-rich smectites, not Fe minerals. This step is thus partially speculative in catalyst identity but literature-based in environmental conditions and precursor logic (Lambert, Gurrieri & Siskin, 1985-like hydrothermal literature summarized in sources 13450 and 13474 of the provided report)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Cyanosulfidic homologation branch from glycinenitrile to alanine nitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-irradiated sulfide mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic homologation setting"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile inventory undergoes formaldehyde-based C1 homologation within cyanosulfidic chemistry to reach the alanine nitrile carbon skeleton.", "reasoning": "Prior feedback noted that a glyconitrile/glycinenitrile branch must not be left disconnected from alanine. The knowledge base explicitly highlights glyconitrile-based cyanosulfidic chemistry as a route toward amino acid synthesis from simple feedstocks. This reaction therefore provides the necessary documented carbon-extension link into alanine nitrile while remaining conservative about mechanistic detail, since the report gives pathway class support more than a single isolated step structure (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018; source 9376 in the provided report)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classical Strecker via hydrothermal acetaldehyde", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced-carbon chemistry supplies acetaldehyde, surface energy chemistry supplies HCN, and classical Strecker synthesis gives alanine nitrile followed by hydrolysis to alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_011", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Phosphoro-Strecker route", "description": "Acetaldehyde enters DAP-enabled phosphoro-Strecker chemistry under neutral surface conditions, yielding a phosphorylated aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_012", "rxn_014"], "k