treated as part of reduced hydrothermal organic inventory\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-mediated CO/CO2 hydrogenation and C-C coupling on reduced iron oxide/iron surfaces produce small aldehydes including acetaldehyde in trace prebiotic inventories.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies acetaldehyde as the key Strecker precursor for alanine and supports hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on magnetite/Fe-bearing minerals as a source of small aldehydes, alcohols, and hydrocarbons. Direct acetaldehyde formation is less specifically documented than general aldehyde formation, so this node is an inventory-level connection rather than a claim of exclusive product selectivity (McCollom & Seewald, 2007; Rushdi & Simoneit, 2001; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Energy-driven HCN generation in surface environments\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated, anoxic, reducing local atmosphere or shallow-pool photochemical setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical and energy-driven reduction/nitridation chemistry generates cyanide feedstock under UV-exposed prebiotic surface conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary explicitly supports HCN availability from UV/energy-driven prebiotic synthesis and reducing-atmosphere experiments as foundational to amino acid formation, including alanine via Strecker chemistry; this node encodes environmental supply of cyanide rather than a single stoichiometrically exact laboratory transformation. TiO2 is included