n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide-like intermediates to the carboxylic acid, yielding alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of \u03b1-aminonitriles to amino acids is the classical second stage of Strecker synthesis and is necessary to make alanine explicit rather than collapsing terminal chemistry into a single node. The literature summary supports aminonitrile hydrolysis as the established route from Strecker intermediates to alanine (Strecker, 1850; Bada, 2013; Parker et al., 2011 re-analysis context for amino acid inventories).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker formation of N-phosphoroalanine nitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-310K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals and diamidophosphate-rich phosphate chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH; selective reaction of aldehydes over ketones\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Diamidophosphate activates aminonitrile formation from acetaldehyde and cyanide, generating a phosphorylated aminonitrile intermediate with improved selectivity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research report explicitly identifies phosphoro-Strecker chemistry as a literature-supported alanine route, with DAP reacting with aldehydes and HCN at neutral pH to form N-phosphoroaminonitriles that hydrolyze to amino acids. This reaction is therefore directly grounded in the provided literature (Krishnamurthy and co-workers; Gibbs et al., 2022 as summarized in the knowledge base).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of N-phosphoroalanine nitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis after concentration/dilution cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis removes the phosphoroamidine/nitrile functionality to release alanine and inorganic phosphate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary explicitly states that N-phosphoroaminonitriles hydrolyze to amino acids. This step is separated from formation to avoid overcompression and to preserve reaction-level fidelity (Gibbs et al., 2022; Krishnamurthy et al., phosphoro-Strecker framework as summarized in the provided report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cannizzaro-derived formamide formation from formaldehyde, formic acid, and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporative surface setting; Cannizzaro-type formaldehyde disproportionation inventory feeding amidation chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde disproportionation yields formate/formic acid, which with ammonia gives formamide under dehydrating surface conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The provided literature explicitly identifies the Cannizzaro pathway as an alternative non-Strecker alanine route in which formaldehyde gives formic acid, formic acid reacts with ammonia to form formamide, and formamide-derived carbon/nitrogen chemistry feeds alanine synthesis with acetaldehyde. This node captures the documented formaldehyde \u2192 formic acid/formamide logic without collapsing the full route (Kebukawa et al., 2013/2017 meteoritic and formamide-pathway literature as summarized in source 5960).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide-acetaldehyde route to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating pool chemistry; route stands for the documented non-Strecker formamide-based conversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formamide-derived carbamyl/carbanion-equivalent chemistry adds to acetaldehyde and, after hydrolytic rearrangement, yields alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically identifies a Cannizzaro/formamide alternative to Strecker synthesis in which formamide-derived reactive species react with acetaldehyde to produce alanine. Because the knowledge summary does not provide the exact discrete intermediate used in that study, this node is kept as the minimal literature-faithful terminal representation rather than inventing unsupported extra intermediates. It is therefore literature-grounded but somewhat schematic (Kebukawa et al., summarized in source 5960).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of pyruvate and glyoxylate in Fe2+-driven protometabolic chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+-rich iron-sulfur mineral environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"inert atmosphere; protometabolic aldol/retro-aldol, hydration/dehydration and redox network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1/C2 carbonyl chemistry in Fe2+-rich hydrothermal solution undergoes network-level aldol and redox transformations to furnish pyruvate and glyoxylate as central keto-acid hubs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary explicitly cites Fe2+-catalyzed prebiotic network chemistry at about 70 degrees C under inert atmosphere, with glyoxylate and pyruvate as important intermediates in alanine-relevant synthesis. Because the report does not specify a single elementary precursor pair for the whole network, this node represents the documented Fe2+-driven protometabolic emergence of pyruvate/glyoxylate from reduced carbon inventory rather than an unsupported one-step mechanism (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019; Keller, Ralser and related protometabolic literature summarized in sources 9400, 9983).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"iron-sulfur mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; NH3 present; formic acid/formate as reductant equivalent\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine/iminium with ammonia followed by reduction to alanine on mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary explicitly includes reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids as a plausible prebiotic route to alanine and identifies pyruvate as the direct keto-acid precursor. This reaction is written specifically as reductive amination, correcting the prior error of mislabeling NH3-only chemistry as transamination. Mineral mediation is included to satisfy the hydrothermal constraints and to reflect iron-sulfur plausibility, though exact mineral-specific alanine yields remain less resolved than the overall pathway (Weber & Miller, 1981/1983 framework for keto-acid amination; Muchowska et al., 2019; source 15293 summary).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Dihydroxyacetone formation from formaldehyde-rich carbonyl chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"hydrothermal condensation of formaldehyde-derived carbonyl inventory\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl condensation/homologation in hydrothermal solution builds C3 ketose inventory including dihydroxyacetone.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary identifies dihydroxyacetone as an experimentally relevant intermediate for alanine production under hydrothermal conditions. This node represents its generation from formaldehyde-rich prebiotic carbonyl chemistry without inventing an unsupported detailed multistep scheme (Larralde et al. and hydrothermal carbohydrate-ammonia literature summarized in sources 10827, 10820).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal dihydroxyacetone-ammonia route to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Al-rich smectite\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"423K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Al-rich smectite and p