l., cyanosulfidic prebiotic chemistry reviews summarized in source 9376).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Conversion of glycolonitrile to glycinenitrile by ammonolysis\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"concentrating pool, cyanide-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonolysis/reductive amination equivalent of glycolonitrile yields aminoacetonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aminoacetonitrile/glycinenitrile is a documented aminonitrile intermediate in prebiotic amino-acid chemistry, and the literature summary identifies both cyanohydrins and \u03b1-aminonitriles as important intermediates. This step is included as a connecting reaction required to make the cyanosulfidic branch chemically explicit; while more detailed mechanistic studies may involve additional reagents or redox steps, the conversion is consistent with prebiotic nitrile chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2016; Bada, 2013).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Homologation of glycinenitrile to alanine nitrile via formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite and borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"condensing surface chemistry; C1 homologation of aminonitrile pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde adds one carbon to the glycinenitrile-derived carbon skeleton through aminonitrile homologation, furnishing alanine nitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary specifically notes stepwise formaldehyde addition from glycine-related precursors toward alanine in formose-ammonia chemistry. Because the exact isolated intermediate sequence is not fully detailed in the provided report, this homologation node is somewhat schematic but remains grounded in the documented role of formaldehyde in building higher amino acids from simpler nitrile/amino intermediates (Lazcano & Miller, 1996; Weissbuch and related formose-ammonia literature summarized in sources 13497, 13498, 9327).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical-style transamination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-303K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous phosphate-buffer-like prebiotic pool; amino transfer equilibrium\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nonenzymatic transamination interconverts pyruvate and alanine in the presence of amino-donor pools, modeling the evolutionary bridge to biological alanine biosynthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature summary explicitly cites non-enzymatic transamination in aqueous phosphate buffers at 25-30 degrees C as relevant to alanine synthesis and the evolutionary transition to biochemistry. The reaction is represented as an equilibrium-style alanine/pyruvate interconversion to reflect amino-donor dependence without introducing unsupported extra molecules; this corrects the earlier misuse of ammonia as a transaminating reagent. The node is included for pathway accounting and evolutionary relevance (source 1024 summary; Moran-group nonenzymatic transamination context; modern alanine transaminase analogy from source 6940).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Wet-dry condensation of alanine to alanylalanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling on mineral interfaces; peptide/depsipeptide-forming regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dehydrative condensation of alanine forms short peptides or related oligomers during evaporation-heating cycles.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly includes ester-mediated and peptide-forming pathways incorporating alanine into depsipeptides and peptides under prebiotic conditions. This node provides the required biochemical assembly connection downstream of alanine production and keeps the full network connected to macromolecular relevance (Forsythe et al., 2015; Rodriguez-Garcia et al., 2015; Frenkel-Pinter et al., 2020; source 21506 summary).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon reduction furnishes acetaldehyde inventory, surface photochemistry supplies HCN, and classical Strecker synthesis produces alanine nitrile followed by hydrolysis to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Phosphoro-Strecker route from acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde enters DAP-mediated phosphoro-Strecker chemistry to form N-phosphoroalanine nitrile, which